{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604440"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:54:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:54:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15836"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15836"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71478"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8527"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15836"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56987"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"8734"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20468"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71478"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vestibular apparatus, which helps maintain balance and spatial orientation, develops from a specialised region of surface ectoderm during embryological development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes when vestibular apparatus development begins?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Week eight of development","Week four of development","Week six of development","Week three of development","Week two of development"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vestibular apparatus begins development in \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek four\u003C/strong\u003E when the otic placode (thickened region of surface ectoderm) invaginates to form the otic pit, which then becomes the otic vesicle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDevelopment occurs too late in \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek eight\u003C/strong\u003E, and too early in \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek two\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek three\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003EWeek six\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect as the initial formation has already occurred by this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe otic vesicle differentiates into dorsal and ventral portions. The dorsal portion forms the semicircular canals through outpouching and fusion, while the ventral portion develops into the utricle and saccule. This complex process of development results in the formation of the balance organs of the inner ear.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The vestibular apparatus develops from the otic placode at week four of embryological development","The semicircular canals form from the dorsal portion of the otic vesicle through outpouching and fusion","The utricle and saccule develop from the ventral portion of the otic vesicle"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Helwany M, Arbor TC, Tadi P. Embryology, Ear. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2023 Aug 8. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557588/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56987"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15836"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56987"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T18:20:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T18:31:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8527"}},"cont